metadata.name: abstraction #61
metadata.description:
Diagrams of patterns on spheres, planets, fields, and platonic solids rendered isometrically. Ink on paper (on js).

Press DOWN to save an SVG suitable for plotting (or laser etching).
Press UP to save a 2400 x 2400 png. If you need a bigger image, zoom out and refresh, the canvas will fit the window.

Physics is fundamentally idealist. We search for simple rules from which the complexities of the universe emerge. But real systems are exceptionally complex, closed-form solutions are the exception. The deeper we dive into the fundamental nature of the universe, the less clear the rules become. Are the rules we've developed fundamental, or are they empirical approximations?

metadata.name: monuMOments #51
metadata.description:
“monuMOments” was inspired by the work of visual artist Penelope Umbrico, seeking a reflection on the era of techno fossils and on the relationship of human beings with technology and the environment as a whole, whether manufactured or natural.  See more in 

“Penelope Umbrico's MONUMENT explores the monolithic state of current technologies in relation to their obsolescence. Umbrico begins with the idea that all technologies - including the electronics we use at home and in the workplace - are in effect “black boxes” whose contents are largely incomprehensible to end users. Although we tend to think of screens as invisible and we never see the workings of our technologies, almost everything we learn and know these days is mediated through the filters of technology. Umbrico aims to demystify the black-box device and to engage the public in creative modes of transforming and visualizing the electronic detritus that accumulates in our homes and in landfills.” (https://www.bricartsmedia.org).

The algorithm initially simulates the static noise of old televisions and from there on, several elements and layers follow one another that, through different blending modes, colors, lights and shadows, shape the final image.

About the ultra rare feature, CASTING OUT NINES refers to the work of the same name done in 2020 that deals with the largest environmental crime in terms of extension that is known in the country, where hundreds of tons of crude oil were spilled on the coast of northeast Brazil.
Each of the nine photographs in the work represent one of the states reached, where a specific color was superimposed.

The colors superimposed on each of the images appeared by chance, or not so much, and were constructed from temporal data and the location of the appearance of the spots on Brazilian beaches. In the RGB palette of “oil” tones, the value of “R” came from the sum of the tens contained in the date of the first oil record in each of the states, as well as the values of “G” and “B” came from the sum of the numbers contained in the geographic coordinates of latitude and longitude, respectively, of the affected locations.

#Main Features

- 16 color schemes “zones”;
* CASTING OUT NINES – 1,5% chance
* NO SIGNAL – 2% chance
* WOODCUT – 3% chance
* GREY SCALE – 3,5% chance
* TAGs | GOLDEN, SILVER, BRONZE and BLOOD – 4% chance each
* SHAKE + - 6% chance
* SHAKE - - 8% chance
* FRAQUENCIES | 9hz, 10hz, 11hz, 12hz, 13hz and 14hz – 10% chance each
  
- 3 canvas formats;
- 4 rotation frequency;
- 3 degrees of granulometry;

#Royalties split: 30% for minters.

Claimmable physical print: Minters of the ultra rare feature will receive an edition of the book AUGUST TIDE and a collection of 9 exclusive prints (20x12 cm each), numbered and signed, about CASTING OUT NINES.
 
The book and the prints can be claimed by DM on Twitter @morbeck_art or by email contato@mateusmorbeck.com

Other interested parties may purchase separately the book or a printed and signed version of their edition.

June 04, 2022

Generative Token by Morbeck for fxhash.

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #147
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

metadata.name: StairWaves #100
metadata.description:
StairWaves is a generative collection imagining abstract stairs built in a wavy nature, with shadows being a key theme. While some waves are quite turbulent, others are just flat.

All shapes in the artwork are built using the same core logic applied in different ways. The method used to draw the waves is also used to draw the shadows, as well as the subtle textures on the surface of the waves. This homogeneous approach ensures a consistent and flowy feel to the final output.

StairWaves is coded entirely in p5.js. 

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: Sketch Book #104
metadata.description:
Sketch Book is a generative collection that imagines an abstract sketch built with lines and shapes in harmony with each other.

It’s called Sketch Book as it started with me sketching a bunch of lines in p5.js and then warping them to give them a natural waviness. The artwork combines subdivision and domain warping techniques before drawing the final lines and shapes on the canvas. 

Sketch Book renders as a fixed resolution output (1000x1200px). Controls (in live view): 

Press [2] to render at 2000x2400px
Press [4] to render at 4000x4800px
Press [8] to render at 8000x9600px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)

metadata.name: Zaratan #37
metadata.description:
The Generative Token chooses between three primitives (cubes, spheres, triangle stripes) and places it along a parametric curve with parameters varying with noise() function as source of smooth motion.

New shapes are added layer after layer with new forms and colors.

At any time the user can pause the generation by pressing 'p', resume it with 'r' and save a 1600x1600 png with 's'.

Sources of variations are:
- primitives choice (3)
- orientation (0, 90, 180, 270 degrees)
- initial conditions
- shapes evolution
- colors evolution (only 10% will be bi-chromatic)


Press:
- 'p' to pause
- 'r' to resume
- 's' to save a 1600x1600 png image

metadata.name: Absorbed #110
metadata.description:
A collaboration between leading British high-end audio brand KEF, generative artist hieroglyphica, and creative studio Parameta, Absorbed embodies the process of noise becoming high-fidelity sound through KEF’s Metamaterial Absorption Technology (MAT™). 

MAT™ makes the KEF sound what it is: absorbing unwanted distortion to deliver pure, accurate sound exactly as the artist intended. Inspired by this intricacy, Absorbed illustrates pseudorandom networks of patterns, slowly emerging and transforming into the maze-like form of MAT™. Clarity is revealed, noise is absorbed – high-fidelity is found.

The noise fields used in Absorbed are of two distinct types: conventional gradient noise and “sinusoidal” noise, an original algorithm developed for this series. The use of animation as artistic medium reflects the artists’ belief that no single frame can capture the full range of complexity found in the tension between sound and noise, and lets collectors observe for themselves this ever-shifting dialogue. A more extensive discussion of the algorithms used in Absorbed can be found in hieroglyphica’s companion article on fx(text).

- spacebar will pause and resume the animation
- s will save a still image of the current frame
- technically minded collectors can consult the index.html file for info on how to render and save high-resolution images
- use of hardware acceleration in Chrome may impact performance

Founded by BBC engineer Raymond Cooke in 1961, KEF is a leading British innovator of high-end audio products including HiFi speakers, subwoofers, architectural speakers, wireless speaker-systems, and headphones. Find out more at kef.com or visit our Discord at discord.com/invite/u48Z9yjY2q.

metadata.name: .cloths (Japan color) #29
metadata.description:
For this Token, I was inspired by Japanese culture and incorporated colors traditionally associated with Japan into the palette.

The traditional Japanese colors, regularly tiled, resemble the scales of Nishikigoi or the patterns of a kimono (furisode) patterns.

The shearing deformation of the tile shapes; shear() makes the colors appear abstract.

The palette is selected from one of the following variations.

01. Ninja(忍者)　02. Tsukimi(月見)　03. Fuji & Moon(富士と月)　04. Urushi(漆)　05. Red Fuji(赤富士)　06. Tonosama(殿様)　07. Daimyo(大名)　08. Cherry Blossom(桜)　09. Autumn Leaves(紅葉)　10. Furisode(振り袖)　11. Nishikigoi(錦鯉)　12. Uji Kintoki(宇治金時)　13. Samurai(侍)

I would be happy if you could feel the beauty of Japan, my birthplace, even a little.



Generative art by @ConatusLab

Built in Javascript with p5.js.

Press 's(S)' to save a png.
